Would love to have backtick syntax for code formatting like what's described here:
[Link|https://github.com/adam-p/markdown-here/wiki/Markdown-Cheatsheet#code-and-syntax-highlighting]

For example, for a block of code, would want to do something like:
{code}
```
def atlassian_is_so_cool:
    return "sure emily, we will give you that which you desire"
```{code}
... and have that render as if it were wrapped in \{code} tags

Similarly, it would be cool to be able to render inline code text (with a grey background) in single backticks, eg:
{code:java}
Guys, I think our method `atlassian_is_so_cool` is having some issues. Let's get it fixed up!!
{code}

Thank you, and I love you guys forever!!

[https://marketplace.atlassian.com/plugins/com.onresolve.jira.groovy.groovyrunner/cloud/overview]

Script Runner is a plugin that would allow for enhanced JQL search functionality. For example if I wanted to search for issues in my current sprint that are blocked I could do:
 {color:#654982}+project = SYSENG AND status != Done AND Sprint in openSprints() AND issueFunction in hasLinks("is blocked by")+{color}

{color:#654982}You can search for blocks recursively as well to show further blocks...{color}

{color:#654982}There is further functionality that may or may not be useful.. a script could be triggered by a ticket getting updated that might cause said script to go update the field of some other ticket.{color}

Simple emoji use in comment fields yields a Server Error.

The message was:

bq. Communications Breakdown
bq. The JIRA server could not be contacted. This may be a temporary glitch or the server may be down. Close this dialog and press refresh in your browser

The server response was:

{noformat}
{"errorMessages":["Internal server error"],"errors":{}}
{noformat}

*Problem:* As a power user, I search a lot using the Search bar in the head of the page. Jira is set up to either interpret or not interpret the input (Smart), but this still fails to deliver the power user JQL experience.

*Possible Solutions: *
  *A)* Have a per-user, per-usergroup, per-server, per-service setting for the Search bar, with the ability to always require correct JQL searches.
  *B)* Evolve the interpreter, to not try to interpret already correct JQL. More rules than that can apply.

*Background Story:* I have Basic Searched and Basic Searched, but I have not found a way to either for a user, for a server, or for groups of users set the "Advanced Search" (named so in the application) the regular search in the head of the Jira webpage. The application is expecting you to never be a power user, and even when it tries to figure out what you are doing, just makes a complete mess out of it. Just having a per-user setting for this would resolve the issue for me and all other power users out there.

For example, a search for:
{noformat}
project = JRASERVER AND text ~ "advanced search"{noformat}
Is actually interpreted as:
{noformat}
project = JRASERVER AND text ~ "project =  AND text ~ \"advanced search\""{noformat}
Link to above example: [jira.atlassian.com|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-44919?jql=project%20%3D%20JRASERVER%20AND%20text%20~%20%22project%20%3D%20%20AND%20text%20~%20%5C%22advanced%20search%5C%22%22]
